“For 7th” That’s the hard part to write. Tommy looked me in the eye and kept it straight. I deeply appreciate his support. I got to give my fitness a chance. It’s not a lack of competing or effort or desire. Right now, as I prep to advance through rounds, it’s about execution and trust in the calculated risk. In hindsight, today’s 51.9 is a great first lap. But I got sleepy - I had the eyes down while the pack I can race with (1:.6) moved away. I had a great finish in the last 100m… but again, I got to give my fitness a chance - Be there at 600m. The guys I get to race now are too good - Olympians. They’re not coming back to me. I need to give myself a chance to fight, not fight back. I felt so in control after the race 🤷🏼‍♂️. Finding the good in my fourth 1:46 of the year - very consistent and progressing well. Excited to embrace the challenge of maintaining a level head and not thinking less of myself, but thinking of myself less. Two weeks of focused training and lifestyle before another great opportunity. Grateful.

Established by a retired detective and corporate lawyer, DRC is seeking new recruits to bolster its professionally disillusioned base of running enthusiasts.

The DRC meets at short notice during traditional working hours and never on weekends. If interested, please leave your name and number to the right of the advertisement for Susie’s services within the red telephone box situated on St Peter’s Square and await further instructions from one of our dossers.

Warmup for this race was brutal with the heat and humidity but have to get used to it at international meets. Was expecting the 1:48 guy to make this interesting but he dropped out a few meters in, so tried to solo as best as I could.

But thankful to represent prep, Fordham, and Empire at an international level. Thankful for all of the family who was able to come out and support in person and back in the states. Shout out to the Morvant Jets for being my club away from home 🫡.
